<DOC><DOCNO> AP890626-0168 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1916EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-26 0577</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0593</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms From Rockies To East Coast, Tropical Storm In Texas</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Tropical Storm Allison rolled ashore Monday in Texas with highwind, torrential rain and high tides as thunderstorms packingdamaging winds and tornadoes formed from Colorado to the East Coast.   Allison's main threat was expected to be heavy rain, with up to10 to 15 inches of rainfall considered possible in eastern Texas andsouthwestern Louisiana before late Tuesday afternoon.   In just 20 minutes, 1.10 inches of rain fell on northern BossierCity, La., and in 6 hours 1.89 inches of rain fell at Galveston,Texas, with 1.21 inches at Houston.   A tornado touched down in Galveston, but no injuries or damagewere reported.   In the Houston area, Allison flooded streets and cut off power to30,000 Houston Lighting andamp; Power Co. customers. Tides 5 feet abovemean sea level closed the Houston Ship Channel from Galveston Bay toHouston. Several schools, including the University of Houston atClear Lake, canceled Monday night classes.   Much of the nation east of the Rockies was under a hot, humid,unstable air mass, just the right ingredients for thunderstorms. Byearly afternoon thunderstorms popped up over many locations fromColorado to the East Coast.   A line of strong thunderstorms reached from eastern Wisconsin tonorthwestern Illinois and northeastern Missouri.   In Wisconsin, scores of confirmed and unconfirmed tornadotouchdowns were reported in the south-central section of the state.   Sheriff's offices reported damage to homes and many trees inRichland and Sauk counties, including a mobile home destroyed southof Richland Center, and damage to numerous barns, small buildings,trees and power lines.   A school addition under construction at Baraboo was toppled byhigh wind, injuring a worker, officials said.   Severe thunderstorms produced heavy damage at Avoca, about 40miles west of Madison, and winds gusted to 60 mph just west ofMonroe.   Thunderstorm winds downed trees and power lines in Eagle, and1{-inch diameter hail was reported in northwestern Milwaukee County.   Numerous thunderstorms developed rapidly across parts ofsoutheastern Kansas, most of the mid- and lower Mississippi Valley,southern Florida, and New York state. A tornado touchdown wasreported near North Miami Beach, Fla.   Severe thunderstorms also formed over parts of eastern Colorado.Hail an inch in diameter fell in Waterton, and 1- to 2-inch hailpelted other parts of central Jefferson County.   Montana continued its run of cool weather with a record low forthe date of 41 degrees at Glasgow.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56degrees at Bellingham, Wash., to 102 at Phoenix and Gila Bend, Ariz.Monday's low for the Lower 48 states was 27 at Leadville, Colo.   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastfrom southeast Missouri to eastern Wisconsin, the central andeastern Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley and the central and northernAppalachians, as well as from the eastern halves of Oklahoma andTexas to the lower Mississippi and Florida. Widely scattered showersand thunderstorms were forecast from northern California to thenorthern Rockies, and in the mountains of Colorado and northern NewMexico.   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted from the PacificNorthwest to northwestern Montana, as well as northern Minnesota,upper Michigan, and along the central and southern coasts ofCalifornia; between 100 and 110 degrees from the desert Southwest tofar southwestern Texas; and in the 80s and 90s in the rest of thenation.</TEXT></DOC>